Without this conviction, the Institutio could never have been penned. Again, if the problem of the decline of eloquence had still been a living issue at the close of the 181 cen· tury, where should we have come upon clearer indications of its existence than in the epigrams of Martial or in the letters of Pliny, which so faithfully mirror the intellectual movements 01 1110 111110 ? Of oratorical decadence, 01 corruption—not a word. The historical works 01 Tacitus himself point in the same direction. In fact, the amount 01 attention paid by these writers to oratorical achieve- ments, the high meed of praise bestowed upon orators, the very number mentioned, prove that the decline of eloquence no longer disturbed their reflections.

Now the Dialogus is, in my judgment, a special contribution‚ perhaps the ablest and profoundest, to this controversy, and hence it was necessarily written at a time when the question was still agitating some of the best minds of literary Rome. But this was no longer the case at the close of Domitian⁷s reign, or in that of Nerva or of Trajan. The Dialogus could, therefore, no more have been composed at this late date, whether by Tacitus or any other · contemporary, than Pei-rault⁷s Paralleles des anciens et des mo· V dernes or Swift's Battle of the Books could have been penned in · 1110 days of Louis XVI. or George Ι.
